part1_states = ['Kentucky','New York','Illinois','California','Texas','Colorado']
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,16))

for i,state in enumerate(part1_states):
    
    plt.subplot(3,3,i+1)
    
    state_fuel_count = power_plants[power_plants.State == state].groupby('primary_fuel').count()['State']
    
    state_fuel_count.plot(kind='bar',color=['grey' if (x < max(state_fuel_count.values)) else 'red' for x in state_fuel_count.values ])
    
    plt.title(state)
    
fig.tight_layout()

fig.suptitle("Count plot of power plants' types in six states", fontsize=18,y = 1.05,color='blue')
    
    
# It can be seen that the above three states are the states have the largest value of cancer cases per 100000 states. 
# Their main power plants are waste, hydro and gas. 
# Meanwhile, Kentucky and Illinois have a large number of coal power plants


# The following three states are the states that have the lowest value of cancer cases per 100000
# the most power plants for them are solar, wind and hydro, which pose less risk of cancer

def generation_sum(fuel):
    df = power_plants.groupby(['State','primary_fuel'])['State','primary_fuel','generation_gwh_2013','generation_gwh_2014','generation_gwh_2015','generation_gwh_2016','generation_gwh_2017'].sum().unstack().fillna(0)

    df.columns = df.columns.droplevel(0)
    df = df1.rename_axis(None, axis=1)
    df = df.apply(lambda x: x / x.sum()).sort_values(by=fuel,ascending=False).iloc[0:25]
    print(set(df.index.values) & set(mean_cancer_cases[:25].index.values))
    print('\nThese states have the Top 25 ' + fuel + ' generation in the US\n')
    print('Meanwhile, their mean cancer cases is also Top 20 in the US')
    print('\n')
    print('The Pearson coefficient between meancases and ' + fuel + ' is', pearsonr(df[fuel][:25], mean_cancer_cases[:25])[0])
    
generation_sum('Gas')

# Among the top 25 states in terms of total Gas generation, nine of them have the top 20 mean cancer cases per 100000 people in the United States
# At the same time, Pearson coefficient is 0.93, which was close to 1

# convert latitude and longitude to state, county

geo = []

for lat,lon in zip(superfund['Latitude'],superfund['Longitude']):
    geo.append((lat,lon))

def trans_lat_lon(geolocation):
    coordinates = geolocation
    results = rg.search(coordinates)
    return results

geo_dict = trans_lat_lon([i for i in geo])

geo_state = [list(geo_dict[i].values())[3] for i in range(len(geo_dict))]
geo_county = [list(geo_dict[i].values())[4] for i in range(len(geo_dict))]

superfund['State'] = geo_state
superfund['Counties'] = geo_county

superfund.head()

# use default parameters

models = [KernelRidge(),ElasticNet(),Lasso(),BayesianRidge(),GradientBoostingRegressor(),LassoLarsIC(),RandomForestRegressor(),xgb.XGBRegressor(),CatBoostRegressor()]

shuff = ShuffleSplit(n_splits=5,test_size=0.2,random_state=42)

columns = ['Name', 'Parameters', 'Train Accuracy Mean', 'Test Accuracy']

first_try = pd.DataFrame(columns = columns)

row_index = 0

for alg in models:
    
    model_name = alg.__class__.__name__
    first_try.loc[row_index,'Name'] = model_name
    first_try.loc[row_index,'Parameters'] = str(alg.get_params())
    
    alg.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
    training_results = np.sqrt(-cross_val_score(alg, X_train, y_train, cv = shuff, scoring= 'neg_mean_squared_error')).mean()
    test_results = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,alg.predict(X_test)))
    
    first_try.loc[row_index, 'Train Accuracy Mean'] = (training_results)
    first_try.loc[row_index, 'Test Accuracy'] = (test_results)
    
    row_index += 1

decimals = 3
first_try['Train Accuracy Mean'] = first_try['Train Accuracy Mean'].apply(lambda x:round(x,decimals))
first_try['Test Accuracy'] = first_try['Test Accuracy'].apply(lambda x: round(x, decimals))
first_try
